  "text": "The Rust trait obligation system works through a carefully orchestrated chain of components that manages trait solving from registration through error reporting.\n\n**Core Data Structure: ObligationForest**\nThe foundation is `ObligationForest` in `compiler/rustc_data_structures/src/obligation_forest/mod.rs`. It manages a forest of obligation nodes, supporting two main operations: adding root obligations and processing pending obligations. It implements a tree structure where each node can spawn child obligations and tracks completion or error states.\n\n**Fulfillment Context and Processing**\nThe `FulfillmentContext` (in `compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/fulfill.rs`) is the main entry point for trait solving. It wraps an `ObligationForest` of `PendingPredicateObligation` nodes and drives the solving process. When `select()` is called, it creates a `FulfillProcessor` that implements the `ObligationProcessor` trait.\n\n**The FulfillProcessor Chain**\n`FulfillProcessor::process_obligation()` is the key method that processes each pending obligation. For trait obligations, it routes to `process_trait_obligation()`, which calls `SelectionContext::poly_select()` to attempt trait selection. The processor handles different predicate kinds (trait, projection, well-formedness, subtyping, etc.) and converts selection results into `ProcessResult` values: `Changed` (obligation satisfied with subobligations), `Unchanged` (ambiguous), or `Error`.\n\n**Selection Pipeline: Candidate Assembly and Matching**\nThe `SelectionContext` (in `compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/mod.rs`) is the core selection engine. It implements the key methods:\n- `poly_select()`: Entry point for selecting a polymorphic trait obligation\n- `candidate_from_obligation()`: Attempts to find a candidate with caching\n- `candidate_from_obligation_no_cache()`: Core logic that assembles and filters candidates\n\nCandidate assembly is handled in `compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/candidate_assembly.rs` with `assemble_candidates()`. This method collects all applicable candidates from:\n- Trait aliases (`assemble_candidates_for_trait_alias`)\n- Impl blocks (`assemble_candidates_from_impls`)\n- Caller bounds (`assemble_candidates_from_caller_bounds`)\n- Builtin candidates for special traits (Sized, Clone, etc.)\n\n**Impl Matching**\nImplementation matching uses `MatchAgainstFreshVars` in `compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/_match.rs`. This implements the `TypeRelation` trait to check if a trait reference structurally matches a freshened impl signature. The matcher allows unbound type variables in the impl but ensures concrete types in the obligation match exactly.\n\n**Candidate Confirmation**\nOnce a candidate is selected, `SelectionContext::confirm_candidate()` in `compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/confirmation.rs` confirms it and generates obligations. For impl candidates, this calls `confirm_impl_candidate()` which unifies output types and collects nested obligations from the impl. Different candidate types (ParamCandidate, ImplCandidate, BuiltinCandidate, ProjectionCandidate, ClosureCandidate, etc.) are confirmed differently.\n\n**Specialization**\nWhen multiple impls apply, specialization rules in `compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/specialize/mod.rs` determine precedence. The specialization graph tracks impl relationships to ensure only the most specific impl is selected.\n\n**Error Reporting**\nUnsatisfied trait bounds are reported by `FulfillmentErrorCode` and handled in `compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/error_reporting/traits/fulfillment_errors.rs` and `mod.rs`. The error reporting system generates detailed diagnostics including:\n- What trait failed to be satisfied\n- Why it failed (unimplemented, unsatisfied bounds, ambiguity)\n- Suggestions for fixes (adding bounds, using different types)\n- On-unimplemented attribute messages\n\n**The Obligation Chain Execution**\nWhen a trait obligation is registered with `FulfillmentContext`, it enters the ObligationForest as a root node. Each `process_obligations()` iteration applies `FulfillProcessor` to pending nodes. A trait obligation flows through: initial registration → trait selection attempt → candidate assembly → impl matching → confirmation with nested obligations → eventual completion or error. Failed obligations generate error entries with their full obligation stack for diagnostic context."
}

